# PrairieLog Frontend Security and State Rule

PrairieLog handles sensitive values such as ingestion tokens and webhook URLs.

The frontend is a demo/developer portal, not a secure secret vault.

## Token Handling

Ingestion tokens are sensitive.

Rules:

* Keep ingestion tokens in memory only
* Do not store tokens in `localStorage`
* Do not store tokens in `sessionStorage`
* Do not store tokens in cookies
* Do not hardcode real production tokens
* Do not log real tokens to the console
* Do not display tokens again after page refresh
* Tell the user to copy the token when it is created

Allowed:

```js
window.PrairieLogState.ingestionToken = tokenResponse.token;
```

Not allowed:

```js
localStorage.setItem("ingestionToken", tokenResponse.token);
sessionStorage.setItem("ingestionToken", tokenResponse.token);
document.cookie = `token=${tokenResponse.token}`;
```

## Webhook URL Handling

Webhook URLs are sensitive.

Rules:

* Allow the user to submit a webhook URL
* Do not store webhook URLs in browser storage
* Do not log webhook URLs to the console
* Do not show full webhook URLs after creation
* Prefer showing destination name/type/status instead

## In-Memory State

Use `state.js` for the current page session.

Example:

```js
window.PrairieLogState = {
  user: null,
  app: null,
  ingestionToken: null,
  alertDestination: null
};
```

This state should reset when the page refreshes.

That is intentional.

## Error Handling

Frontend API errors should be displayed clearly.

Do:

* Show status code
* Show backend message if available
* Show a friendly explanation

Do not:

* Expose raw tokens
* Expose webhook URLs
* Dump sensitive request headers into the UI

## Browser Token Warning

Any page that generates or uses an ingestion token should explain:

"Your ingestion token is kept only in this browser page session. Refreshing or closing the page clears it. Copy it now because it will not be shown again."

## Public Frontend Warning

Because this is a browser frontend, users should understand that browser-side tokens are visible to anyone using that app.

For production applications, recommend:

* backend proxy logging
* scoped ingestion tokens
* rate limits
* token revocation
* app-specific tokens
